\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

As with all CLIs,
 functions,
 constants,
 and general context is available going forward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the ideal place to test out classes & functions you have built to see how they handle various scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common way to dynamically pull in updated code is the :load command.
 It reads a .scala file and executes every line as if you typed it into the REPL manually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
scala> :load MyScript.scala
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// All classes,
 objects,
 and variables in MyScript.scala are now updated in your session.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 due to scala's sophistication,
 we can tell the scala-cli to dynamically reload any libraries it has loaded whenever they change:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
scala-cli repl .
 --watch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can also simply redefine things on the fly,
 such as classes,
 in the REPL:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
object Config { val url = "http://new.com" } // replaces existing Config values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Tab Completion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The repl has a very sophisticated tab completion feature.
 Simply partially type a class/funtion/variable/whatever,
 and press tab to get a list of possible completions.
 Saves on type,
 and also helps to explore classes and methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Inside the REPL,
 you can:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Test Snippets:
 Paste in a complex match statement to see if it catches your edge cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Inspect Types
\series default
:
 Use :type myVariable to see exactly what the compiler thinks you’ve created.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Tab-Complete
\series default
:
 Hit Tab to see every method available on an object (perfect for exploring the 200+ methods on a String).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Quick Imports
\series default
:
 Just like in your code,
 you can import sttp.client3.* and start making live API calls from the command line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the ultimate "Pragmatic" tool for debugging:
 move from "I think this works" to "I know this works" in seconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Configuration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several frameworks available for scala that provide customized REPLs with their own initialization code,
 etc.
 However,
 we're going to stick to the OG here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the standard REPL we have been discussion,
 you can provide 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preloaded
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 code that runs whenever a REPL is opened.
 For example,
 if we write some initial code in 
\series bold
init.scala
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import sttp.client3._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import doobie._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import doobie.implicits._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import cats.effect.IO
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Pre-define your standard backend and database connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val backend = HttpClientSyncBackend()
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val xa = Transactor.fromDriverManager[IO](...) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
println("Environment loaded:
 sttp and doobie ready.")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can load it with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
scala-cli repl --dep ...
 -i init.scala
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact,
 we can define all sorts of helper methods and classes that we can then use in the repl console with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
//> using dep com.softwaremill.sttp.client3::core:3.9.0
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
//> using dep org.tpolecat::doobie-core:1.1.0
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import sttp.client3._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import doobie._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import doobie.implicits._
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// 1.
 Define a helper Class for API calls
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
case class Api(token:
 String) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  val base = basicRequest.auth.bearer(token)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def getUser(id:
 Int) = base.get(uri"https://api.com/users/$id")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// 2.
 Define a helper Method for DB status
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
def checkDb(xa:
 Transactor[cats.effect.IO]):
 Unit = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  import cats.effect.unsafe.implicits.global
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  val result = sql"SELECT 1".query[Int].unique.transact(xa).unsafeRunSync()
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  println(s"Database Status:
 $result (Success)")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
println("--- Dev Environment Loaded ---")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
println("Try:
 val api = Api(
\backslash
"my-secret
\backslash
")")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Configuration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see current settings:
 :settings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To change a setting:
 :settings -deprecation or :settings -Xlint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see the "Power" mode (internal compiler debug):
 :power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note:
 Power mode is for advanced users;
 it gives you access to the compiler's internal symbol table.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

You can use the import $dep syntax to pull in a library on the fly.
 You don't need to restart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Pull in the sttp Circe (JSON) module mid-session
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import $dep.`com.softwaremill.sttp.client3::circe:3.9.0`
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Now you can immediately use it
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import sttp.client3.circe._
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also update log levels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import ch.qos.logback.classic.{Level,
 Logger}
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Get the root logger and silence it,
 or set to DEBUG to see SQL/HTTP traces
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val root = LoggerFactory.getLogger(org.slf4j.Logger.ROOT_LOGGER_NAME).asInstanceOf[Logger]
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
root.setLevel(Level.DEBUG) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Now Doobie will likely print every SQL statement it executes!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 if you're unsure what's currently available in your session:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
:imports:
 Lists all the import statements currently active in your session.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
:type:
 Check the type of any variable to see if a module's implicit conversion has "taken over" your object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
:javap:
 If you want to see the "real" Java methods on a class you just loaded.
\end_layout

